{"id":"2102.08479","submitter":"Enrico Antonini","authors":"Aditya Dhoot, Enrico G. A. Antonini, David A. Romero, Cristina H. Amon","title":"Optimizing wind farms layouts for maximum energy production using\n  probabilistic inference: Benchmarking reveals superior computational\n  efficiency and scalability","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Energy, Vol. 223, 120035, 2021","doi":"10.1016/j.energy.2021.120035","report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Successful development of wind farms relies on the optimal siting of wind\nturbines to maximize the power capacity under stochastic wind conditions and\nwake losses caused by neighboring turbines. This paper presents a novel method\nto quickly generate approximate optimal layouts to support infrastructure\ndesign decisions. We model the quadratic integer formulation of the discretized\nlayout design problem with an undirected graph that succinctly captures the\nspatial dependencies of the design parameters caused by wake interactions. On\nthe undirected graph, we apply probabilistic inference using sequential\ntree-reweighted message passing to approximate turbine siting. We assess the\neffectiveness of our method by benchmarking against a state-of-the-art branch\nand cut algorithm under varying wind regime complexities and wind farm\ndiscretization resolutions. For low resolutions, probabilistic inference can\nproduce optimal or nearly optimal turbine layouts that are within 3% of the\npower capacity of the optimal layouts achieved by state-of-the-art\nformulations, at a fraction of the computational cost. As the discretization\nresolution (and thus the problem size) increases, probabilistic inference\nproduces optimal layouts with up to 9% more power capacity than the best\nstate-of-the-art solutions at a much lower computational cost.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 16 Feb 2021 22:36:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-19"}
